    <h2>Section 1:  Overview</h2>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                1. Identify the project/program, governing process(es) and team members involved in project planning.
                <ul>
                    <li>a. Program Name:  @ViewBag.partner.name</li>
                    <li>b. Designation (e.g., VE ####, G00###, etc.): @ViewBag.partner.address1</li>
                    <li>c. Program Leader/Manager: @ViewBag.Manager</li>
                    <li>
                        d. Governing process (e.g., Triage, Value Engineering, Standard Transition Process-STP, Other):
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62353 /> Standard Transition Process-STP
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62354 /> Triage
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62355 /> Value Engineering
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62356 /> Other
                    </li>
                    <li>e. Identify the functional representatives involved in Project Planning (e.g., E&T, M&PM, ISC-VE, GS&I, SS):</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                2. Provide a general description of the project including the following:
                <ul>
                    <li>a. Does access code VU not have a description?</li>
                    <li>
                        b. If the Project is Transition related, which type of activity is this?
                        <br /><input type="checkbox"  @ViewBag.ActivityType270/> Make to Make Transition (HON to HON)
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.ActivityType269/> Make to Buy (Outsourcing)
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.ActivityType267 /> Buy to Buy (Supplier to Supplier)
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <input type="checkbox" /> Build to Print (BTP)
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <input type="checkbox" /> Build to Spec (ASL)
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <input type="checkbox" /> Supplier Reposition
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.ActivityType268/>Buy to Make (In sourcing)
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.ActivityType266 />Other
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        c. Is there an assist or non-recurring payment?
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35500_Yes /> Yes
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35500_No /> No
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        d. Does this product involve new designs or reuse?
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35501_Yes /> Yes
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35501_No /> No
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        e. In the part a programmble electronic component OR is it used on any of the following military platforms?
                        <br /><input type="checkbox"  /> US Government technology demonstrations
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" /> B-1B, B-2, B-21
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" /> F-15SE, F/A-18E/F, F-22, F-23, F-17
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" /> EA-18G
                        <br /><input type="checkbox" /> Abrams 1
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h2>Section 2: Transitions to China</h2>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                1. Does the transition/reposition contemplate movement of any parts to or within China for manufacture?
                <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35505_Yes /> Yes.
                <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35505_No /> No. Skip the remainder of this Section 2 and proceed to Section 3.
            </li>
            <li>
                2. Is the drawing assigned a Military technology export classification (TEC) code, regardless of the country of current design authority (CDA) to be confirmed by
                the Approver/Export Compliance for this Section? A military technology export classification is any Department of State ITAR/USML item, as well as any Department
                of Commerce 500 or 600 series item.
                <br />Instructions: Approver for this Section to mark "Y" in the "USML/500/600 (Y/N)" column of the "Project Scope" tab of the Scope and Export Data file.
                <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35508_Yes /> Yes. Part cannot be transitioned. Skip the remainder of this Section 2 for this particular part.
                <br /><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35508_No /> No.
            </li>
            <li>
                3. For each part contemplated for transition/reposition to or within China, please answer the following:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        a. In the CID file, was a usage code other than "C" (e.g., "CM", "MC", "M", "OT") found in the "Smart Usage Code" column of the "Workbook" tab?
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35506_Yes /> Yes. Provide end-use platform and customer information in the "China Optics" tab of the Project Scope file embedded in Section 1, Item 2.c of this checklist (see
                        above).
                        <br />
                        Instructions: Find the Application/Model information listed under the "Military Rolled Up" column of the "Workbook" tab of the CID file. Insert this information in
                        the Project Scope file.
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35506_No /> No. Skip the remainder of this Section 2 for this particular part.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        b. Has General Counsel, Aerospace Global Operations and Transitions approved transition/reposition of this particular part to China?
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35509_Yes /> Yes. Proceed with transition of this particular part.
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35509_No /> No. Part cannot be transitioned.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>


    <h2>Section 3: Export and Import (STP Phase 2 exit requirement)</h2>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                1. Are the new suppliers listed on the Denied Parties List (Transition Manager must run check against the
                Denied Parties List in accordance with Aerospace Policy AP-1025)?
                <br />
                N/A. The parts are being transitioned to a Honeywell site.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35512_Yes /> Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35512_No /> No.
            </li>
            <li>
                2. Will any hardware manufacturing machines or equipment, tooling, fixtures and/or test equipment be
                provided to the receiving Honeywell site or new supplier?
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35513_Yes />  Yes.
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        i.      If Yes, is the receiving Honeywell site or new supplier located offshore AND will the machine/tooling/test equipment be provided free of charge or at a reduced cost, AND will result in imports into the United States?
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35514_Yes /> Yes. Provide the name of the person who is most familiar with the transition of the machine/tooling/test equipment mentioned above.
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35514_No /> No.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35513_No /> No.
            </li>
            <li>
                3. Will the receiving Honeywell site or new supplier return the manufactured hardware exclusively to Honeywell in the US?
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35515_Yes /> Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35515_No /> No. They will transfer hardware to located in .
            </li>
            <li>
                4. Has the receiving Honeywell site or new supplier obtained all necessary export authorizations to return the
                manufactured hardware to Honeywell in the U.S. or to the entities identified in Question #3?
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62357 /> Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62359 /> Pending. The proposed receiving Honeywell site or supplier is working on obtaining the necessary local country
                export authorizations.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62358 /> No. Obtain confirmation from local export focal(s) that no export authorizations are required.
            </li>
            <li>
                5. For any parts transitioned/repositioned outside the US, which will be shipped back to a US site, has the
                HTSUS (Harmonized Tariff Schedule of the United States) submittal been completed to prevent customs delays? Please
                go the following link and reference the Instructions Tab.
                <a hrfe="https://teamsites2013.honeywell.com/sites/ICFS/ES/Shared%20Documents/Forms/AllItems.aspx">https://teamsites2013.honeywell.com/sites/ICFS/ES/Shared%20Documents/Forms/AllItems.aspx</a>
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35517_Yes /> Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35517_No /> No.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h2>Section 4:  IP Compliance (STP Phase 2 exit requirement)</h2>
    <p>
        <h3>A.   Third Party Proprietary Information (Buy to Buy & Make to Buy & Buy to Make & OIP)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                1. Can Honeywell and the new supplier (if applicable) execute this project using only documents and information that were/are created solely by Honeywell or the new supplier (if applicable) or are clearly within the public domain?  Note:  The execution of the project cannot rely on the use of any documents or information that are considered "proprietary," in whole or in part, to Honeywell's current supplier or another third party.  When responding to this question, consider all aspects of the project, from planning through production, including product specifications, product design documentation, documents needed for obtaining and reviewing proposals/quotes, responding to supplier inquiries, conducting design reviews, performing test/qual/cert activities, etc.  If any documents planned for use on this project are marked (or suspected to be) "Proprietary" or "Confidential" to a third party, mark "No/Not Sure".
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35521_Yes /> Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35521_No /> No/Not sure, contact IP Counsel for further reevaluation.
                <ul>
                    <li><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62362 /> i.  IP Counsel contacted on [ date ], risk was cleared with recommendation to proceed.</li>
                    <li><input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox62363 /> ii. IP Counsel contacted on [ date ], risk acknowledged and characterized for consideration by transition business stakeholders.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <br/>
        <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />
        <h3>B.    Reverse Engineering (Buy to Buy & Buy to Make)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                2. As part of this project, will Honeywell need to "Reverse Engineer" the current supplier's part or provide the current supplier's part to the new supplier? Note: For the purposes of this question, "Reverse Engineering" activities include obtaining information about the design, construction or operation of the part through inspection, testing, measurement, disassembly or reverse engineering of the current supplier's part for use in any aspects of the project including design, test, qualification, certification, and production.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35524_Yes /> Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35524_No /> No. Skip remainder of Sub-Section B Reverse Engineering and proceed to Sub-Section C People and Stored Information.
            </li>
            <li>
                3. Has the Sourcing L&C representative (if unsure, verify with the cognizant commodity manager or use assignment list to identify the Sourcing L&C representative) reviewed the Contract, PIA and purchase orders of the current supplier to ensure there are no prohibitions related to Honeywell using the part for these purposes and provided guidance on information that may be shared during reverse-engineering process?
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35525_Yes />  Yes.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35525_No /> No. Please explain why not:_______
            </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>C.     People and Stored Information (Buy to Buy & Buy to Make)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                4. Does any Honeywell employee that will participate in the project (including members of the Engineering & Technology, Marketing & Product Management, and Integrated Supply Chain functions) have knowledge of the
                current supplier's proprietary information that will be relevant to the employee's role in the project? Note: When responding to this question, consider all aspects of the project, from planning through production, including creating
                documents for and reviewing proposals/quotes, responding to supplier inquiries, conducting design reviews, performing test/qual/cert activities, etc
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35527_Yes /> Yes. Consult with the Souring L&C representative to provide the guidance on what proprietary information can be shared with the supplier.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35527_No /> No.
            </li>
            <li>
                5. Does Honeywell have stored information (e.g., PDM, Team Center, etc.) that is proprietary to the current supplier and that is relevant to the part or product?
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35528_Yes /> Yes. Consult with the Souring L&C representative to provide the guidance on what proprietary information can be shared with the supplier.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35528_No /> No.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>D.    Third Party Patents (Buy to Buy & Buy to Make)</h3>
        Is this a Build to Specification transition?
        <br />
        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35529_No /> No. Skip remainder of Sub-Section D and proceed to Sub-Section E.
        <br />
        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35529_Yes /> Yes. Proceed to next question.
        <ul>
            <li>
                6. Do you have documentation identifying when Honeywell first sold and/or delivered a product or assembly containing this part?
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35530_Yes /> Yes. Identify the date of delivery and/or sale and identity of supporting document(s):
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                First sale date:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  First delivery date:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Supporting document(s):
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35530_No />  No. Do you have documentation, such as a schematic, which identifies the first production-approved version of the part?
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35534_No /> i. No.
                        <br />
                        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35534_Yes /> ii. Yes.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Date of first production-approved design:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Supporting document(s):
                       
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
      
        <li>
            7.   Does the part or associated documentation include any patent markings?  Note: Patent markings can be on the part itself (such as by etching or on a name plate), on its packaging or packaging inserts, and possibly a company's web site page for the part. Patent markings are commonly recited in a manner such as - "US Patent No. #,###,###" or "covered by one or more of the following US Patents: #,###,###; #,###,###; and #,###,###".
            <br />
            <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35537_Yes /> Yes, consult with IP counsel and provide patent numbers or patent markings:
            <br />
            <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35537_No /> No.
        </li>
        <li>
            8.   Is patent infringement a significant risk for any part(s) to be transitioned?  High patent infringement risk parts include newer parts that include specific technology or features that are only currently available from the current supplier.  Low patent infringement risk parts include those parts that have been in production for a significant period of time (more than 20 years) years and include technology or features that are commonly available from other suppliers.  Note:  To determine if a current supplier owns any patents, use Google Patents and enter the supplier name in the search field.
            <br />
            <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35538_Yes /> Yes, consult with IP counsel and provide details regarding the current supplier and part(s) to be transitioned.
            <br />
            <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35538_No /> No.
        </li>
        </ul>
        <br/>
        <h3>E.    Third Party Licenses (Buy to Buy & Make to Buy & OIP)</h3>
        Does the transition scope include transfer of any software, tooling or test/manufacturing equipment?
        <br />
        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35539_No /> No. Skip remainder of Sub-Section E and proceed to Section 5.
        <br />
        <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35539_Yes />  Yes. Proceed to next question.
        <ul>
            <li>
                9. Are there any third party intellectual property licenses that will need to be transferred or assigned to the new supplier?  Consult with engineering, testing, supply chain, and licensing teams to determine if any third party intellectual property licenses apply to the software, tooling or test/manufacturing equipment to be transferred.  Note: We need to identify any third party licenses that will need to be transferred or assigned to the new supplier.  These licenses can include (1) software licenses for software used in manufacturing, testing, or as part of product operation, (2) data/documentation licenses for third party information (such as other supplier's manuals) for use in assembly or testing, or (3) patent licenses needed to manufacture or sell the part.  When responding to this question, consider whether we use any third party intellectual property, such as software or information, in any aspect of our manufacturing process, from planning through production, including creating documents for and reviewing proposals/quotes, responding to supplier inquiries, conducting design reviews, performing test/qual/cert activities.  To determine if such third party licenses exist, we will need to review with the responsible engineering, testing, supply chain, and licensing teams.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35542_Yes /> Yes, consult the Sourcing L&C representative to review the identified licenses to determine what can be transferred or assigned the licenses to the new supplier.
                <br />
                <input type="checkbox" @ViewBag.Checkbox35542_No /> No. Skip remainder of Sub-Section E and proceed to Section 5.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>


    <h2>Section 5:  Customer Contracts (STP Phase 2 exit requirement)</h2>
    <p>
        The contract review section will require that both the CID and CFDB Final documents have been completed.
        <ul>
            <li>
                1. Embed final CFDB, CID, and Entanglement summary files, or if files are too large, please provide links with access for LC&E Checklist approvers:
            </li>
            <li>
                2. Insert document link to project folder where due diligence and documentation is stored:
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

